''Valis II'' was first released for the [[TurboGrafx-16#TurboGrafx-CD/CD-ROM²|PC Engine CD-ROM²/TurboGrafx-CD]] in Japan by Telenet on June 23, 1989, and later in North America by [[NEC]] on May 23, 1990.<ref name="PCEFv2i6">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/pc-engine-fan-june-1989/page/6/mode/2up|title=New: ヴァリスII|magazine=[[PC Engine Fan]]|volume=2|issue=6|publisher=[[Tokuma Shoten]]|date=June 1, 1989|pages=6–9|lang=ja}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=May 2022}} The home computer version was first released in Japan for the [[PC-8800 series|PC-8801]] on July 8, 1989, then for the [[MSX|MSX2]] and [[PC-9800 series|PC-9801]] on August 5, and later for the [[X68000]] on November 18 under the name ''Valis: The Fantasm Soldier II''.{{efn|{{nihongo|夢幻戦士 ヴァリスII|Mugen Senshi: Varisu Tsū}}}}<ref name="ValisIIHG101"/><ref name="TechPC-88msvII"/><ref name="Techv8i83">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/technopolis-1989-07/01_journal-1989-07/page/n13/mode/2up|title=夢幻戦士 ヴァリスII (画面は88版のちのです)|magazine={{ill|Technopolis (magazine)|lt=Technopolis|ja|テクノポリス (雑誌)}}|volume=8|issue=83|publisher=[[Tokuma Shoten]]|date=July 1989|pages=12–13|lang=ja}}</ref><ref name="MSXMag71">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/MSXmagazine198909S_201711/page/n18/mode/1up|title=New Soft: 夢幻戦士ヴァリスII|magazine={{ill|MSX Magazine|lt=MSX Magazine|ja|MSXマガジン}}|issue=71|publisher=[[ASCII Corporation]]|date=September 1989|page=19|lang=ja}}</ref> These versions contained more graphic cutscenes, while the X68000 version featured improved visuals.<ref name="ValisIIHG101"/><ref name="Oh!X81">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/OhMZOhx19861989/Oh%21X_1989-11/page/n85/mode/1up|title=The Softouch - Software Information / 新作ソフト情報 - ★夢幻戦士ヴァリスII|magazine={{ill|Oh!X|lt=Oh!X|ja|Oh!X}}|issue=81|publisher=[[SoftBank Creative]]|date=November 1989|pages=84–85|lang=ja}}</ref> The release of the computer versions were also supplemented with a soundtrack album, distributed in Japan by [[Toshiba EMI]] on August 27.<ref name="VGMOa"/>

A remake for the [[Sega Mega Drive/Genesis]], developed by Imaginative System Create (I.S.C.), was first released in Japan by Laser Soft as ''SD Valis''{{efn|{{nihongo|ＳＤヴァリス|Esu Dī Varisu}}}} on February 14, 1992.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=https://sega.jp/fb/segahard/md/soft_licensee.html|script-title=ja:ソフトウェア一覧（ソフトライセンシー発売）&#124; メガドライブ|encyclopedia=SEGA HARD Encyclopedia|publisher=[[Sega]]|date=2022|access-date=2022-05-04|lang=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200626053415/https://sega.jp/fb/segahard/md/soft_licensee.html|archive-date=2020-06-26|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=CRV|url=http://gdri.smspower.org/wiki/index.php/I.S.C.|title=I.S.C.|work=Game Developer Research Institute|date=April 17, 2011|access-date=2022-05-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009182958/http://gdri.smspower.org/wiki/index.php/I.S.C.|archive-date=2016-10-09|url-status=live}}</ref> Telenet also released the game through its subsidiary [[Renovation Products]] in North America as ''Syd of Valis'' in April 1992.<ref name="SydofValisHG101"/><ref name="GSW"/><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/Sega_Visions_Volume_01_Issue_08_1992-05_Sega_US/page/n57/mode/1up|title=Around The Corner|magazine=[[Sega Visions]]|volume=1|issue=8|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=May–June 1992|page=56}}</ref> A European release was planned by [[UbiSoft]], as part of a multi-game licensing deal with Renovation, but it was never officially released in the region for unknown reasons.<ref name="MegaT1">{{cite magazine|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File:MegaTech_UK_01.pdf&page=6|title=News – Ubisoft in exclusive Megadrive Game Import Deal Shocker!|magazine=[[MegaTech]]|issue=1|publisher=[[Ascential|EMAP]]|date=December 1991|page=6}}</ref><ref name="SF1">{{cite magazine|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3ASegaForce_UK_01.pdf&page=10|title=Gutter Talk – Ubi-Renovation-Soft|magazine=[[Sega Force]]|issue=1|publisher=[[Europress Impact]]|date=January 1992|page=10}}</ref> It features the same gameplay and plot as the TurboGrafx-CD original, but the character design was changed to a [[super deformed]] (SD) style, while the North American version incorrectly identifies Yuko as "Syd" and reuses artwork of another Telenet release called ''The Sugoroku '92: Nariagari Trendy''{{efn|{{nihongo|~ザスゴロク´92~ なりトレ|Suguroku '92: Naritore}}}} for its front cover.<ref name="SydofValisHG101"/>{{citation needed|date=May 2022}}

A compilation titled ''Valis Visual Collection'' was released in 1993 by Telenet for the PC Engine CD-ROM², featuring the visual scenes from ''Valis II''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/weekly-famitsu-no.-219-february-26th-1993/page/38/mode/1up|title=NEW GAMES CROSS REVIEW: ヴァリス コレクション集 (PCエンジンCD-ROM)|magazine=[[Famitsu]]|issue=219|publisher=[[ASCII Corporation]]|date=February 26, 1993|page=38|lang=ja}}</ref> The original PC Engine version, as well as the home computer versions, were re-released in digital form for [[Microsoft Windows]] through [[D4 Enterprise]]'s Project EGG service.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kitamura|first=Takakazu|url=https://game.watch.impress.co.jp/docs/20020828/egg.htm|title=Project EGG、MSX「ヴァリス」など第9回ラインナップを公開 9月初旬にメガドライブ移植版「ワンダラーズ・フロム・イース」をリリース|work={{ill|Game Watch|lt=GAME Watch|ja|GAME Watch}}|publisher={{ill|Impress Corporation|lt=Impress Corporation|ja|インプレス}}|date=August 28, 2002|access-date=2022-05-04|language=ja|archive-date=2020-09-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200922052757/https://game.watch.impress.co.jp/docs/20020828/egg.htm|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nlab.itmedia.co.jp/games/gsnews/0211/03/news02.html|title=クリムゾン,ゼクサス…ツウだぜ,プロジェクトEGG!|work=[[SoftBank Group|SoftBank Games]]|publisher={{ill|ITmedia|lt=ITmedia|ja|ITmedia}}|date=November 3, 2002|access-date=2022-05-04|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020091208/https://nlab.itmedia.co.jp/games/gsnews/0211/03/news02.html|archive-date=2019-10-20|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.4gamer.net/news/history/2007.07/20070705205549detail.html|title=【リリース】EGG，7月10日に「夢幻戦士ヴァリスII」を配信開始|work=[[4Gamer.net]]|publisher=Aetas Inc.|date=July 5, 2007|access-date=2022-05-04|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090505191248/https://www.4gamer.net/news/history/2007.07/20070705205549detail.html|archive-date=2009-05-05|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.4gamer.net/games/008/G000896/20091110010/|title=「プロジェクトEGG」PC-9801版「夢幻戦士ヴァリスII」を配信開始|work=[[4Gamer.net]]|publisher=Aetas Inc.|date=November 10, 2009|access-date=2022-05-04|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713084503/https://www.4gamer.net/games/008/G000896/20091110010/|archive-date=2019-07-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dengekionline.com/elem/000/000/449/449922/|title=Project EGGでX68000版『夢幻戦士ヴァリスII』とPC-98版『Wind'sSeed ～風の種～』が配信|work=Dengeki Online|publisher=Kadokawa Game Linkage|date=January 24, 2012|access-date=2022-05-04|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713084645/https://dengekionline.com/elem/000/000/449/449922/|archive-date=2019-07-13|url-status=live}}</ref> The game was included as part of the ''Valis: The Fantasm Soldier Complete'' compilation for Windows, published by Sunsoft in 2004 under a limited run of 2000 copies, which came bundled with a bonus CD and a figure.<ref name="MSXForce8">{{cite magazine|last=Venom|first=Dr.|url=https://archive.org/details/msx_force_12/msx_force_8/page/n20/mode/1up|title=Valis - Ascensão E Queda De Uma Serie|magazine=MSX Force|issue=8|publisher=[[ASCII Corporation]]|date=August 2006|pages=21–27|lang=pt}}</ref><ref name="4G.net">{{cite web|url=https://www.4gamer.net/games/008/G000896/20111124028/|title=プロジェクトEGG，「夢幻戦士ヴァリスCOMPLETE PLUS」を500本限定で発売|work=[[4Gamer.net]]|publisher=Aetas Inc.|date=November 24, 2011|access-date=2022-05-04|language=ja|archive-date=2019-07-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713102938/https://www.4gamer.net/games/008/G000896/20111124028/|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2011, D4 Enterprise re-released the compilation with ''SD Valis'' and an additional title as ''Valis: The Fantasm Soldier Complete Plus'', which came bundled with a CD soundtrack instead.<ref name="4G.net"/> The PC Engine version was also made available by [[Sunsoft]] as part of the "PC Engine Archives" line on the [[PlayStation Network]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jp.playstat